                                <p> By Paul Eckert</p>
                                <p> SEOUL, Sept 23 (Reuters) - For South Koreans, the appeal of  reunification with North Korea is partly negated by the  knowledge that the cherished goal would cost the South's  taxpayers billions of dollars.</p>
                                <p> Economists' estimates of the cost of reunification -- based  on the experience of Germany -- range from $10 billion to more  than $1 trillion, depending on how long it takes the capitalist  South and the communist North to unify.</p>
                                <p> That harsh reality has not been eliminated by a recent  unprecedented wave of inter-Korean rapprochement moves, but the  good news is that South Korea might not have to bear the burden  alone.</p>
                                <p> Recently, a successful Japan-North Korea summit has raised  the prospect of large-scale Japanese aid and investment with  the normalisation of ties after a half century of bitterness.</p>
                                <p> The European Union, a key source of humanitarian aid for  North Korea, gave its blessing on Sunday to South Korean and  Japanese engagement with the North. Russia has said it would  help connect the Koreas with Europe via its Trans-Siberian  Railroad.</p>
                                <p> North Korea has even helped its cause lately with a mixture  of economic policy changes that look like Chinese-style reform  and with a diplomatic outreach that could solve long-standing  regional security problems and disarm critics of engagement.</p>
                                <p> WITHOUT REFORM, STAGNATION</p>
                                <p> South Korea, with an economy about 27 times bigger than the  North and more han twice the population, has spent about $110  million each year on economic aid to the North since 1995.  Trade on terms favourable to the North topped $400 million last  year.</p>
                                <p> South Korean President Kim Dae-jung, who has spearheaded  the "Sunshine Policy" of engaging North Korea, argues that the  aid is a down payment on unification that will reduce costs  later.</p>
                                <p> The $1.2 trillion unification price tag was an estimate by  a Western think tank of what it would cost to raise North  Korea's per capita income to 60 percent of that of the South.  South Korean estimates range from $10 billion to $650 billion  over 10 years.</p>
                                <p> "The cost of reunification will depend on the situation and  process on the peninsula, and the economic situation at the  time of a unification," said Korea University professor Nam  Sung-wook.</p>
                                <p> Nam, an expert on the North's economy, said a sudden  collapse of North Korea will be most costly "since all fields  including roads, industry, agriculture and other areas must be  rebuilt".</p>
                                <p> South Korea's central bank estimated the North Korean  economy grew 3.7 percent in 2001, its third straight year of  growth.</p>
                                <p> But the performance reflected a rebound from previous  negative years and was achieved largely thanks to foreign aid,  with most experts predicting stagnation without reforms.</p>
                                <p> NORTH CAN HELP ITSELF</p>
                                <p> In July, North Korea implemented price and wage reforms  that South Korean analysts said represented nascent  China-inspired steps to introduce incentives to the state-run  economy.</p>
                                <p> Last week, North Korea said it had granted the city of  Sinuiju on its border with China special powers for 50 years so  it can develop as a free commercial, science and tourist  centre.</p>
                                <p> To encourage much-needed foreign investment, North Korea  said foreigners would have the same rights as residents in  Sinuiju.</p>
                                <p> The North Korean moves will take time to show whether they  will be effective in reversing the country's decline.</p>
                                <p> But analysts say the reforms will have an immediate and  positive impact on the North's behaviour.</p>
                                <p> "North Korea will have to cooperate with neighbouring  countries such as South Korea and Japan, as well as the U.S.A.,  since the reforms will need a large amount of funds," Nam said.</p>
                                <p> In addition to compensation from Japan for colonial rule in  Korea -- estimated by some as as much as $10 billion and  expected once Tokyo and Pyongyang formally normalise ties --  North Korea could tap more funds if it resolves lingering  security problems.</p>
                                <p> Pyongyang's offer to repatriate ageing Japanese hijackers  it has harboured since 1970 could clear the way for the removal  of North Korea from the U.S. list of state sponsors of  terrorism, enabling the North to join international financial  agencies.</p>
                                <p> North Korean membership in the International Monetary Fund  and eligibility for World Bank loans would require U.S.  approval -- a further incentive for Pyongyang to address  Washington's concerns about missiles and nuclear proliferation,  Nam said.    </p>
